udes parts of Boston's [[Roxbury, Boston|Roxbury]], [[Back Bay, Boston|Back Bay]] and [[Fenway\u2013Kenmore|Fenway]] neighborhoods.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jonsantiago.org/|title=Jon Santiago for State Rep {{!}} Jon Santiago believes in doing more for Roxbury, the South End, Fenway, and Back Bay.|website=jonsantiago.org|access-date=7 January 2019}}</ref> His 2018 victory in the [[Primary election|Democratic primary]] unseated the chamber's assistant majority leader<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://malegislature.gov/People/Profile/B_R1|title=Representative Byron Rushing|website=malegislature.gov|access-date=7 January 2019}}</ref> [[Byron Rushing]], who had represented the district for 35 years, starting in 1983.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://electionstats.state.ma.us/elections/search/year_from:1982/year_to:2018/office_id:8/district_id:23770|title=PD43+ \" Search Elections|website=PD43+|access-date=7 January 2019}}</ref> Santiago had been a State House [[Internship|intern]] for Rushing before challenging him to his seat.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2019/01/01/five-freshman-lawmakers-watch-beacon-hill/Yq0ETEZzQJIE8DfT05VHfI/story.html|title=Five freshman lawmakers to watch on Beacon Hill \u2013 The Boston Globe|last=Reporter|first=Victoria McGrane-|website=Boston Globe|access-date=8 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nUpon taking office, Santiago continued to serve as a [[Residency (medicine)|resident]] physician in [[emergency medicine]] for the [[Boston Medical Center]], arguing that such a job informs his legislation, especially when it comes to matters of [[public health]] like the [[opioid epidemic]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSince 2013, Santiago is a [[Captain (United States O-3)|captain]] in the [[US Army Reserve]]. He previously served as a volunteer [[community health]] specialist to the [[Peace Corps]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newpolitics.org/jon-santiago/|title=Jon Santiago|website=New Politics|access-date=8 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Santiago, Jon}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Massachusetts House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Democrats]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{short description|American politicians}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Jon Santiago\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = \n| alt =\n| state_house = Massachusetts\n| district = 9th Suffolk\n| term_start = January 2, 2019\n| term_end =\n| predecessor = [[Byron Rushing]]\n| successor = \n| module = \n  {{Infobox medical person | child=yes <!-- or embed=yes or subbox=yes -->\n  | profession = [[Residency (medicine)|Resident]] physician\n  | field = [[Emergency medicine]]\n  | work_institutions = [[Boston Medical Center]]\n  | specialism = }}\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = [[Puerto Rico]], U.S.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jonsantiago.org/meet-jon/|title=Meet Jon - Jon Santiago for State Rep|website=Jonsantiago.org|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref>\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = American\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| education = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Texas at Austin]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]]), [[University of Washington]] ([[Master of Public Health|MPH]]), [[Yale University]] ([[Doctor of Medicine|MD]])<ref>[https://www.linkedin.com/in/jon-santiago-19655624/] {{dead link|date=March 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Jon Santiago''' is an American physician and politician serving as the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[Massachusetts House of Representatives|Massachusetts state representative]] for the 9th Suffolk district since 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://malegislature.gov/Legislators/Profile/J_S2|title=Representative Jon Santiago|website=malegislature.gov|access-date=7 January 2019}}</ref> His district mostly comprises the [[South End, Boston|South End]] neighborhood of [[Boston]], though it also includes parts of Boston's [[Roxbury, Boston|Roxbury]], [[Back Bay, Boston|Back Bay]] and [[Fenway\u2013Kenmore|Fenway]] neighborhoods.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jonsantiago.org/|title=Jon Santiago for State Rep {{!}} Jon Santiago believes in doing more for Roxbury, the South End, Fenway, and Back Bay.|website=jonsantiago.org|access-date=7 January 2019}}</ref> His 2018 victory in the [[Primary election|Democratic primary]] unseated the chamber's assistant majority leader<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://malegislature.gov/People/Profile/B_R1|title=Representative Byron Rushing|website=malegislature.gov|access-date=7 January 2019}}</ref> [[Byron Rushing]], who had represented the district for 35 years, starting in 1983.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://electionstats.state.ma.us/elections/search/year_from:1982/year_to:2018/office_id:8/district_id:23770|title=PD43+ \" Search Elections|website=PD43+|access-date=7 January 2019}}</ref> Santiago had been a State House [[Internship|intern]] for Rushing before challenging him to his seat.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2019/01/01/five-freshman-lawmakers-watch-beacon-hill/Yq0ETEZzQJIE8DfT05VHfI/story.html|title=Five freshman lawmakers to watch on Beacon Hill \u2013 The Boston Globe|last=Reporter|first=Victoria McGrane-|website=Boston Globe|access-date=8 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nUpon taking office, Santiago continued to serve as a [[Residency (medicine)|resident]] physician in [[emergency medicine]] for the [[Boston Medical Center]], arguing that such a job informs his legislation, especially when it comes to matters of [[public health]] like the [[opioid epidemic]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSince 2013, Santiago is a [[Captain (United States O-3)|captain]] in the [[US Army Reserve]]. He previously served as a volunteer [[community health]] specialist to the [[Peace Corps]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newpolitics.org/jon-santiago/|title=Jon Santiago|website=New Politics|access-date=8 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Santiago, Jon}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Massachusetts House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Democrats]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Iamjonsantiago", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated Profession from Resident to Attending to reflect most current professional standing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jon_Santiago"}
{"title_page": "Barre des \u00c9crins", "text_new": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name            = Barre des \u00c9crins\n| photo           = Barre des \u00c9crins & Glacier Blanc.JPG\n| photo_caption   = The Barre des \u00c9crins (4,102 m) in Hautes Alpes, France and the Glacier Blanc\n| photo_size      = 250\n| elevation_m     = 4,102\n| elevation_ref   = <ref name=\"peaklist\">[http://peaklist.org/WWlists/ultras/EuroCoreP1500m.html \"Europe Ultra-Prominences\"]. Peaklist.org. Retrieved 2014-05-24.</ref>\n| prominence_m    = 2,045\n| prominence_ref  = <ref name=\"peaklist\"/>\n| listing         = [[Ultra prominent peak|Ultra]]\n| location        = [[Hautes-Alpes]], [[France]]\n| range           = [[Dauphin\u00e9 Alps]]\n| map             = France\n| map_caption     = France\n| map_size        = 270\n| label_position  = left\n| coordinates     = {{coord|44|55|21|N|06|21|36|E|type:mountain_region:FR_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| range_coordinates = \n| coordinates_ref = <ref name=\"peaklist\"/>\n| first_ascent    = 25 June 1864 by [[Adolphus Warburton Moore|A. W. Moore]], [[Horace Walker]] and [[Edward Whymper]] with guides [[Michel Croz]], [[Christian Almer]] Senior and Christian Almer Junior.\n| easiest_route   = snow/rock climb\n}}\n\nThe '''Barre des \u00c9crins''' (4,102 m) is a mountain in the [[French Alps]] with a peak at 4102m altitude. It is the highest peak of the [[Massif des \u00c9crins]] and the [[Dauphin\u00e9 Alps]] and the most southerly alpine peak in Europe that is higher than 4,000 m. It is the only 4,000 m mountain in France that lies outside the [[Mont Blanc Massif]]. Before the annexation of [[Savoy]] in 1860 it was the highest mountain in France.\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File:Barre des \u00c9crins - South face.jpg|thumb|left|The south face of Barre des \u00c9crins]]\n\n===Location===\nThe Barre des \u00c9crins is the highest peak in the [[Provence-Alpes-C\u00f4te d'Azur]] region including all of [[Occitania]] and the Southern Alps. It is located in the commune of [[Pelvoux]] and is situated near the [[Drainage divide]] between the [[Durance]] and the ''V\u00e9n\u00e9on''. This divide passes 250 metres west of the summit, along the [[ridge]] that leads to the summit of the sub-peak ''D\u00f4me des \u00c9crins'' (4088 metres). The south face of the mountain is rocky while the north face is ice as it is the starting point of the [[Glacier Blanc]].\n\nThe mountain is surrounded by four glaciers: to the north-west is the ''Bonne Pierre glacier'', to the north-east the ''Glacier Blanc'', to the south-west the ''Glacier du Vallon de la Pilatte'', and finally in the south-east the [[Glacier Noir]]. It is separated from the ''Snow Dome of \u00c9crins'' (4015 m) by the ''Lory Gap'' (3974 m) to the west, the ''Barre Noir'' (3751 m) by the ''\u00c9crins Gap'' (3661 m) to the north-east and by ''Fifre'' (3699 m) via the ''Col des Avalanches'' (3499 m) to the south.\n\n===Geology===\nThe mountain consists of [[Migmatite|migmatized]] [[gneiss]], an acidic rock composed of [[quartz]]-[[feldspar]]. On the upper slopes there is an [[Amphibole|amphibolic]] face over the top of the migmatized gneiss forming the top. These formations overlap a large [[granite]] [[Pluton]] that forms the summit of Pelvoux.<ref>Geological Map of France at 1:50000 consulted on InfoTerre (Saint-Christophe-en-Oisans page). {{in lang|fr}}</ref><ref>J.-C. Barf\u00eatry and A. P\u00e9cher, [http://ficheinfoterre.brgm.fr/Notices/0822N.pdf Notice on the Saint-Christophe-en-Oisans page], 1984, BRGM, p. 21\u201323, online 10 December 2006, consulted on 6 February 2013 {{in lang|fr}}</ref><ref>Maurice Gidon, [http://www.geol-alp.uiad.fr/h_oisans/_lieux/veneon/Ecrins.html ''The Barre des \u00c9crins and the right bank of the V\u00e9n\u00e9on height''], 1 June 2010, online 10 July 2011, consulted on 6 February 2013 {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe \u00c9crins were discovered by geographers belatedly in the 19th century when they were the highest point in France ([[Savoy]] being part of the [[Kingdom of Sardinia]] at that time). The mountains are actually located on the borders of the [[Oisans]] and [[Brian\u00e7onnais]] with the highest point completely in Brian\u00e7onnais. They were sometimes called \"point of Arsines\" by locals.\n\nThe Englishmen [[Adolphus Warburton Moore|A. W Moore]], [[Horace Walker]], and [[Edward Whymper]], guided by [[Michel Croz]] from [[Chamonix]] and [[Christian Almer]] from [[Switzerland]], made the first ascent of the Barre des \u00c9crins on 25 June 1864. They cut steps on the north face of the Barre until they reached the top of the eastern edge via the ''Whymper corridor''. They then reached the top of this high ridge which was composed of very unstable rocks. Edward Whymper described the ascension in his book ''Scrambles Amongst the Alps in the Years 1860-69''.<ref name=\"Goedeke\">Richard Goedeke, ''4000 des Alpes'', Libris, coll. Les Guides Libris, June 2007, 22 pages.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=6HYSAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=edward+whymper&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CBoQ6AEwAGoVChMI9IWplZicyQIV4yGmCh1g7gDA#v=onepage&q=edward%20whymper&f=false ''Scrambles Amongst the Alps in the Years 1860-69''], Edward Whymper, Chapter IX p. 201-221</ref>\n\n[[William Auguste Coolidge]] made the first direct climb up the north face of the Barre des Ecrins in July 1870 by cutting 500 steps.<ref>[http://www.summitpost.org/barre-des-ecrins/150265 Barre des \u00c9crins], ''summitpost.org''.</ref>\n\nThe first ascent without a guide is credited to Frederick Gardiner in 1878 accompanied by Charles and Lawrence Pilkington.\n\nThe southern face was climbed for the first time in 1880 by [[Pierre Gaspard (mountaineer)|Pierre Gaspard]] together with [[Henri Duhamel]]. The south pillar, a part of the Black glacier ending at the top, was climbed for the first time in 1944 by the famous couple of climbers Jeanne and Jean Franco.<ref name=\"Goedeke\"/>\n\n== Ascent ==\n[[File:Glacier Noir.jpg|thumb|South face of the Barre (on the right). Below is ''Coolidge Peak'' and ''Le Fifre''.]]\n\nThe Barre des \u00c9crins attracts many climbers and has many routes to the top.<ref>Topo Mountaineering, [http://www.camptocamp.org/summits/38591/fr/barre-des-ecrins#voies-d-ascension The Ways to the top]. {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\nThe mountain is traditionally scaled from the ''Pr\u00e9 de Madame Carle'' in the valley of Ailefroide. The normal route climbs the entire length of the [[Glacier Blanc]]. This is a much-used route, because it is the usual way to the D\u00f4me des \u00c9crins, one of the most easily climbed 4,000 m alpine peaks. It starts from the Refuge des \u00c9crins and climbs the north face almost up to the Lory saddle (3,974&nbsp;m), where the routes to the D\u00f4me and the Barre divide. The ascent of the Barre continues by a rocky [[Arete (landform)|ar\u00eate]] all the way to the summit. The guides from ''La B\u00e9rarde'' have equipped the ''Col des \u00c9crins'' with cables allowing them to bring their clients to the summit.\n\nOther more challenging routes to the summit exist, such as the South Face rated AD (Fairly Difficult). The quality of the rock on the mountain ranges from poor to average and especially on the South Face of the mountain the risk of [[rockfall]] is significant.\n\nIt is possible to climb the ''Direct Coolidge'' in late spring directly to the summit with crampons and an ice axe. Depending on snow conditions, this route can also be done on skis.\n\nThe south-north traverse of the Barre des \u00c9crins bar is also one of the classic routes of the massif.\n\nIn summer it is possible to climb a steep path on the south face with the ''Pilier Sud'' being the most traveled route.\n\nThe record for an ascent on foot is 1 hour 55 minutes by Math\u00e9o Jacquemoud in June 2012, starting from Pr\u00e9 de Madame Carle (1874 m) by the normal route of the D\u00f4me and the Whymper corridor. He beat the old record by Hubert Fievet (2 hours 3 minutes in 1998).<ref>[http://matheojacquemoud.com/2012/06/17/record-a-la-barre-des-ecrins/ A record on the barre des \u00c9crins]. {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\nThe record for round-trip ski mountaineering is 2 hours 51 minutes by Nicolas Bonnet in 2009 from the Pr\u00e9 de Madame Carle.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oCQh0zwH_y4 Record of \u00c9crins alpine skiing 2009]. {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Wikiecrins.jpg|thumb|center|upright=3.2|The \u00c9crins and the [[Glacier Blanc]]]]\n\n== Longest Line of Sight ==\nThe Barre des \u00c9crins is the subject of the longest photographed and recognised line of site on Earth.  In July 2016, Marc Bret took a photograph of the mountain from the [[Pic de Finestrelles]] in the Pyrenees, some 443&nbsp;km distant. [https://beyond-horizons.org/2016/08/03/pic-de-finestrelles-pic-gaspard-ecrins-443-km/]\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Alps | left =  | break = }}\n*[[List of 4000 metre peaks of the Alps]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.summitpost.org/show/mountain_link.pl/mountain_id/86 The Barre des \u00c9crins on SummitPost]\n* [http://www.vallouimages.com/vallouimages.net/barre-ecrins/ecrins-01.htm Climbing the Barre des \u00c9crins in pictures] {{in lang|fr}}\n* {{4000er.de|3}}\n{{Commons category|Barre des \u00c9crins}}\n\n{{Ultras of Europe}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barre Des Ecrins}}\n[[Category:Alpine four-thousanders]]\n[[Category:Mountains of the Alps]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Hautes-Alpes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name            = Barre des \u00c9crins\n| photo           = Barre des \u00c9crins & Glacier Blanc.JPG\n| photo_caption   = The Barre des \u00c9crins (4,102 m) in Hautes Alpes, France and the Glacier Blanc\n| photo_size      = 250\n| elevation_m     = 4,102\n| elevation_ref   = <ref name=\"peaklist\">[http://peaklist.org/WWlists/ultras/EuroCoreP1500m.html \"Europe Ultra-Prominences\"]. Peaklist.org. Retrieved 2014-05-24.</ref>\n| prominence_m    = 2,045\n| prominence_ref  = <ref name=\"peaklist\"/>\n| listing         = [[Ultra prominent peak|Ultra]]\n| location        = [[Hautes-Alpes]], [[France]]\n| range           = [[Dauphin\u00e9 Alps]]\n| map             = France\n| map_caption     = France\n| map_size        = 270\n| label_position  = left\n| coordinates     = {{coord|44|55|21|N|06|21|36|E|type:mountain_region:FR_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| range_coordinates = \n| coordinates_ref = <ref name=\"peaklist\"/>\n| first_ascent    = 25 June 1864 by [[Adolphus Warburton Moore|A. W. Moore]], [[Horace Walker]] and [[Edward Whymper]] with guides [[Michel Croz]], [[Christian Almer]] Senior and Christian Almer Junior.\n| easiest_route   = snow/rock climb\n}}\n\nThe '''Barre des \u00c9crins''' (4,102 m) is a mountain in the [[French Alps]] with a peak at 4102m altitude. It is the highest peak of the [[Massif des \u00c9crins]] and the [[Dauphin\u00e9 Alps]] and the most southerly alpine peak in Europe that is higher than 4,000 m. It is the only 4,000 m mountain in France that lies outside the [[Mont Blanc Massif]]. Before the annexation of [[Savoy]] in 1860 it was the highest mountain in France.\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File:Barre des \u00c9crins - South face.jpg|thumb|left|The south face of Barre des \u00c9crins]]\n\n===Location===\nThe Barre des \u00c9crins is the highest peak in the [[Provence-Alpes-C\u00f4te d'Azur]] region including all of [[Occitania]] and the Southern Alps. It is located in the commune of [[Pelvoux]] and is situated near the [[Drainage divide]] between the [[Durance]] and the ''V\u00e9n\u00e9on''. This divide passes 250 metres west of the summit, along the [[ridge]] that leads to the summit of the sub-peak ''D\u00f4me des \u00c9crins'' (4088 metres). The south face of the mountain is rocky while the north face is ice as it is the starting point of the [[Glacier Blanc]].\n\nThe mountain is surrounded by four glaciers: to the north-west is the ''Bonne Pierre glacier'', to the north-east the ''Glacier Blanc'', to the south-west the ''Glacier du Vallon de la Pilatte'', and finally in the south-east the [[Glacier Noir]]. It is separated from the ''Snow Dome of \u00c9crins'' (4015 m) by the ''Lory Gap'' (3974 m) to the west, the ''Barre Noir'' (3751 m) by the ''\u00c9crins Gap'' (3661 m) to the north-east and by ''Fifre'' (3699 m) via the ''Col des Avalanches'' (3499 m) to the south.\n\n===Geology===\nThe mountain consists of [[Migmatite|migmatized]] [[gneiss]], an acidic rock composed of [[quartz]]-[[feldspar]]. On the upper slopes there is an [[Amphibole|amphibolic]] face over the top of the migmatized gneiss forming the top. These formations overlap a large [[granite]] [[Pluton]] that forms the summit of Pelvoux.<ref>Geological Map of France at 1:50000 consulted on InfoTerre (Saint-Christophe-en-Oisans page). {{in lang|fr}}</ref><ref>J.-C. Barf\u00eatry and A. P\u00e9cher, [http://ficheinfoterre.brgm.fr/Notices/0822N.pdf Notice on the Saint-Christophe-en-Oisans page], 1984, BRGM, p. 21\u201323, online 10 December 2006, consulted on 6 February 2013 {{in lang|fr}}</ref><ref>Maurice Gidon, [http://www.geol-alp.uiad.fr/h_oisans/_lieux/veneon/Ecrins.html ''The Barre des \u00c9crins and the right bank of the V\u00e9n\u00e9on height''], 1 June 2010, online 10 July 2011, consulted on 6 February 2013 {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe \u00c9crins were discovered by geographers belatedly in the 19th century when they were the highest point in France ([[Savoy]] being part of the [[Kingdom of Sardinia]] at that time). The mountains are actually located on the borders of the [[Oisans]] and [[Brian\u00e7onnais]] with the highest point completely in Brian\u00e7onnais. They were sometimes called \"point of Arsines\" by locals.\n\nThe Englishmen [[Adolphus Warburton Moore|A. W Moore]], [[Horace Walker]], and [[Edward Whymper]], guided by [[Michel Croz]] from [[Chamonix]] and [[Christian Almer]] from [[Switzerland]], made the first ascent of the Barre des \u