ute, because it is the usual way to the D\u00f4me des \u00c9crins, one of the most easily climbed 4,000 m alpine peaks. It starts from the Refuge des \u00c9crins and climbs the north face almost up to the Lory saddle (3,974&nbsp;m), where the routes to the D\u00f4me and the Barre divide. The ascent of the Barre continues by a rocky [[Arete (landform)|ar\u00eate]] all the way to the summit. The guides from ''La B\u00e9rarde'' have equipped the ''Col des \u00c9crins'' with cables allowing them to bring their clients to the summit.\n\nOther more challenging routes to the summit exist, such as the South Face rated AD (Fairly Difficult). The quality of the rock on the mountain ranges from poor to average and especially on the South Face of the mountain the risk of [[rockfall]] is significant.\n\nIt is possible to climb the ''Direct Coolidge'' in late spring directly to the summit with crampons and an ice axe. Depending on snow conditions, this route can also be done on skis.\n\nThe south-north travers of the Barre des \u00c9crins bar is also one of the classic routes of the massif.\n\nIn summer it is possible to climb a steep path on the south face with the ''Pilier Sud'' being the most traveled route.\n\nThe record for an ascent on foot is 1 hour 55 minutes by Math\u00e9o Jacquemoud in June 2012, starting from Pr\u00e9 de Madame Carle (1874 m) by the normal route of the D\u00f4me and the Whymper corridor. He beat the old record by Hubert Fievet (2 hours 3 minutes in 1998).<ref>[http://matheojacquemoud.com/2012/06/17/record-a-la-barre-des-ecrins/ A record on the barre des \u00c9crins]. {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\nThe record for round-trip ski mountaineering is 2 hours 51 minutes by Nicolas Bonnet in 2009 from the Pr\u00e9 de Madame Carle.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oCQh0zwH_y4 Record of \u00c9crins alpine skiing 2009]. {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Wikiecrins.jpg|thumb|center|upright=3.2|The \u00c9crins and the [[Glacier Blanc]]]]\n\n== Longest Line of Sight ==\nThe Barre des \u00c9crins is the subject of the longest photographed and recognised line of site on Earth.  In July 2016, Marc Bret took a photograph of the mountain from the [[Pic de Finestrelles]] in the Pyrenees, some 443 km distant. [https://beyond-horizons.org/2016/08/03/pic-de-finestrelles-pic-gaspard-ecrins-443-km/]\n==See also==\n{{portal|Alps | left =  | break = }}\n*[[List of 4000 metre peaks of the Alps]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.summitpost.org/show/mountain_link.pl/mountain_id/86 The Barre des \u00c9crins on SummitPost]\n* [http://www.vallouimages.com/vallouimages.net/barre-ecrins/ecrins-01.htm Climbing the Barre des \u00c9crins in pictures] {{in lang|fr}}\n* {{4000er.de|3}}\n{{Commons category|Barre des \u00c9crins}}\n\n{{Ultras of Europe}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barre Des Ecrins}}\n[[Category:Alpine four-thousanders]]\n[[Category:Mountains of the Alps]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Hautes-Alpes]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: travers \u2192 traverse", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barre_des_%C3%89crins"}
{"title_page": "Border League (baseball)", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{Unreferenced|date=April 2009}}\n{{Refimprove|date=April 2009}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Border League''' was the name of two 20th century circuits in [[North America]]n [[minor league baseball]].\n\n==1912\u20131913 league in Michigan and Ontario==\nThe first, also known as the Eastern Michigan League, was a Class D minor league in 1912 and 1913 at the [[Canada\u2013United States border|Canada\u2013US border]]. It was composed of five teams from [[Michigan]] and one from [[Windsor, Ontario]]. This six-team league never really got off the ground, playing a minimal 35 game schedule. The league lost one [[Michigan]] team that disbanded in 1913. This action helped cause the league's downfall. There was no known effort to organize the league in 1914.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Border_League|title=Border League - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n===1912-1913 cities and teams===\n*[[Mount Clemens, Michigan]]: [[Mount Clemens Bathers]] 1912-1913\n*[[Port Huron, Michigan]]: [[Port Huron Independents]] 1912-1913\n*[[Pontiac, Michigan]]: [[Pontiac Indians]] 1912-1913\n*[[Windsor, Ontario]]: 1912-1913\n*[[Wyandotte, Michigan]]:[[Wyandotte Alkalis]] 1912-1913\n*[[Ypsilanti, Michigan]]: 1913\n\n==1946-1951 Post-World War II league based in New York, Ontario and Quebec==\nThe name was revived for a post-[[World War II]]  Class C circuit that operated from 1946 through 1951 before shutting down. It was represented by nine cities, five from across the Canada\u2013US border (four from [[Ontario]] and one from [[Quebec]]) and four from the state of [[New York (state)|New York]]. The four New York, teams, along with the [[Kingston, Ontario]], squad were able to make the full run. The [[Ottawa Senators (baseball)|Ottawa Senators]] entry won three of the league's six titles.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nThe league proved to be a good solid competitive group for the first five years. Attendance was good, the league drew over 1,600,000 fans the first five years before finally disbanding on July 16, 1951.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===1946-1951 cities and teams===\n*[[Auburn, New York]]: [[Auburn Cayugas]] 1946-1950, [[Auburn Falcons]] 1951\n*[[Cornwall, Ontario]]: [[Cornwall Canadians]] 1951\n*[[Geneva, New York]]: [[Geneva (NY) Red Birds|Geneva Red Birds]] 1947, [[Geneva Robins]] 1948-1951\n*[[Granby, Quebec]]: [[Granby Red Sox]] 1946\n*[[Kingston, Ontario]]: [[Kingston Ponies]] 1946-1951\n*[[Ogdensburg, New York]]: [[Ogdensburg Maples]] 1946-1951\n*[[Ottawa, Ontario]]: [[Ottawa Nationals (baseball)|Ottawa Nationals]] 1947, [[Ottawa Senators (baseball)|Ottawa Senators]] 1948-1949, Ottawa Nationals 1950\n*[[Sherbrooke, Quebec]]: [[Sherbrooke Canadiens (baseball)|Sherbrooke Canadiens]] 1946\n*[[Watertown, New York]]: [[Watertown Athletics]] 1946-1951\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n''This article is based on the [https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Border_League \"Border League\"] article at Baseball-Reference.com Bullpen. The Bullpen is a wiki, and its content is available under the [[GNU Free Documentation License]].''\n\n==External link==\n\n[https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Border_League Baseball Reference]\n\n{{Professional Baseball}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Border League (Baseball)}}\n[[Category:Defunct baseball leagues in Canada]]\n[[Category:Defunct minor baseball leagues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Baseball leagues in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Baseball leagues in Michigan]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{Unreferenced|date=April 2009}}\n{{Refimprove|date=April 2009}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Border League''' was the name of two 20th century circuits in [[North America]]n [[minor league baseball]].\n\n==1912\u20131913 league in Michigan and Ontario==\nThe first, also known as the Eastern Michigan League, was a Class D minor league in 1912 and 1913 at the [[Canada\u2013United States border|Canada\u2013US border]]. It was composed of five teams from [[Michigan]] and one from [[Windsor, Ontario]]. This six-team league never really got off the ground, playing a minimal 35 game schedule. The league lost one [[Michigan]] team that disbanded in 1913. This action helped cause the league's downfall. There was no known effort to organize the league in 1914.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Border_League|title=Border League - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n===1912-1913 cities and teams===\n*[[Mount Clemens, Michigan]]: [[Mount Clemens Bathers]] 1912-1913\n*[[Port Huron, Michigan]]: [[Port Huron Independents]] 1912-1913\n*[[Pontiac, Michigan]]: [[Pontiac Indians]] 1912-1913\n*[[Windsor, Ontario]]: 1912-1913\n*[[Wyandotte, Michigan]]:[[Wyandotte Alkalis]] 1912-1913\n*[[Ypsilanti, Michigan]]: 1913\n\n==1946-1951 Post-World War II league based in New York, #ntario and Quebec==\nThe name was revived for a post-[[World War II]]  Class C circuit that operated from 1946 through 1951 before shutting down. It was represented by nine cities, five from across the Canada\u2013US border (four from [[Ontario]] and one from [[Quebec]]) and four from the state of [[New York (state)|New York]]. The four New York, teams, along with the [[Kingston, Ontario]], squad were able to make the full run. The [[Ottawa Senators (baseball)|Ottawa Senators]] entry won three of the league's six titles.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nThe league proved to be a good solid competitive group for the first five years. Attendance was good, the league drew over 1,600,000 fans the first five years before finally disbanding on July 16, 1951.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===1946-1951 cities and teams===\n*[[Auburn, New York]]: [[Auburn Cayugas]] 1946-1950, [[Auburn Falcons]] 1951\n*[[Cornwall, Ontario]]: [[Cornwall Canadians]] 1951\n*[[Geneva, New York]]: [[Geneva (NY) Red Birds|Geneva Red Birds]] 1947, [[Geneva Robins]] 1948-1951\n*[[Granby, Quebec]]: [[Granby Red Sox]] 1946\n*[[Kingston, Ontario]]: [[Kingston Ponies]] 1946-1951\n*[[Ogdensburg, New York]]: [[Ogdensburg Maples]] 1946-1951\n*[[Ottawa, Ontario]]: [[Ottawa Nationals (baseball)|Ottawa Nationals]] 1947, [[Ottawa Senators (baseball)|Ottawa Senators]] 1948-1949, Ottawa Nationals 1950\n*[[Sherbrooke, Quebec]]: [[Sherbrooke Canadiens (baseball)|Sherbrooke Canadiens]] 1946\n*[[Watertown, New York]]: [[Watertown Athletics]] 1946-1951\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n''This article is based on the [https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Border_League \"Border League\"] article at Baseball-Reference.com Bullpen. The Bullpen is a wiki, and its content is available under the [[GNU Free Documentation License]].''\n\n==External link==\n\n[https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Border_League Baseball Reference]\n\n{{Professional Baseball}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Border League (Baseball)}}\n[[Category:Defunct baseball leagues in Canada]]\n[[Category:Defunct minor baseball leagues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Baseball leagues in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Baseball leagues in Michigan]]\n", "name_user": "Skilgis1900", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1946-1951 Post-World War II league based in New York, #ntario and Quebec", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Border_League_(baseball)"}
{"title_page": "Ridv\u00e1n", "text_new": "{{for|the Turkish given name|Ridvan}}\n{{short description|Twelve-day festival in the Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Faith, commemorating Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h's declaration that he was a Manifestation of God}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed sidebar}}\n'''Ri\u1e0dv\u00e1n''' ({{lang-ar|\u0631\u0636\u0648\u0627\u0646}} {{transl|ar|Ri\u1e0dw\u00e1n}}; [[Persian language|Persian]] [[Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed orthography|transliteration]]: Rezv\u00e1n, {{IPA-fa|\u027eezv\u0252\u02d0n}}) is a twelve-day festival in the [[Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Faith]], commemorating [[Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h]]'s declaration that he was a [[Manifestation of God]].<ref name=\"SmithRidvan\">{{cite encyclopedia |last= Smith |first= Peter |authorlink= Peter Smith (historian) |encyclopedia= A concise encyclopedia of the Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Faith |title= Ridvan |year= 2000 |publisher= Oneworld Publications |location= Oxford |pages= [https://archive.org/details/conciseencyclope0000smit/page/296 296\u2013297] |isbn= 1-85168-184-1 |url= https://archive.org/details/conciseencyclope0000smit/page/296 }}</ref> In the [[Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed calendar]], it begins at sunset on the 13th of Jal\u00e1l, which translates to the 20th or 21st of April, depending on the date of the [[March equinox]] (exactly one month on the Gregorian calendar after the equinox).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bahai-library.com/holy_days_calendar_students |title=Baha'i Dates 172\u2013221 B.E. |website=Baha'i Library |language=en-US |access-date=2018-04-20}}</ref> On the first, ninth and twelfth days of Ridv\u00e1n, work and school should be suspended.<ref name=\"esslemont_1\">{{cite book |author= Esslemont, J.E. |year= 1980 |title= Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h and the New Era |edition= 5th |publisher=Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Publishing Trust |location=Wilmette, Illinois, USA |isbn= 0-87743-160-4 |url= http://reference.bahai.org/en/t/je/BNE/bne-147.html | pages = 182\u2013183}}</ref>\n\n\"Ridv\u00e1n\" means [[paradise]], and is named for the [[Garden of Ridv\u00e1n, Baghdad|Garden of Ridv\u00e1n]] outside [[Baghdad]], where Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h stayed for twelve days after the [[Ottoman Empire]] exiled him from the city and before commencing his journey to [[Constantinople]].<ref name=\"rob1_1\">{{cite book |first=Adib |last= Taherzadeh |year= 1976 |title= The Revelation of Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h, Volume 1 |publisher= George Ronald |location=Oxford, UK |isbn= 0-85398-270-8 |page= 259 |url= http://www.peyman.info/cl/Baha%27i/Others/ROB/V1/p257-282Ch16.html#p259}}</ref>\n\nIt is the holiest Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed festival, and is also referred to as the \"Most Great Festival\" and the \"King of Festivals\".\n\n==History==\n===Context===\nIn 1844 Siyyid [[\u02bbAl\u00ed-Muhammad of Shiraz]] proclaimed that he was the \"[[B\u00e1b]]\" ({{lang-ar|\"Gate\"}}), after a [[Shi\u02bba Islam|Shi\u02bba]] religious concept. His followers were therefore known as [[B\u00e1bism|B\u00e1b\u00eds]].  The B\u00e1b's writings introduced the concept of \"[[He whom God shall make manifest]]\", a Messianic figure whose coming, according to Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00eds, was announced in the scriptures of all of the world's great religions.<ref name=\"eor\">{{cite encyclopedia | last = Hutter | first = Manfred | editor = Ed. Lindsay Jones | encyclopedia = Encyclopedia of Religion | title = B\u0101b\u012bs | edition = 2nd | year = 2005 | publisher = [[Macmillan Reference USA]] | volume = 2 | location = Detroit | pages = 727\u2013729 | isbn = 0-02-865733-0 | url = https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofre0000unse_v8f2 }}</ref><ref name=\"esslemont\">{{cite book |author= Esslemont, J.E. |year= 1980 |title= Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h and the New Era |edition= 5th |publisher=Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Publishing Trust |location=Wilmette, Illinois, USA |isbn= 0-87743-160-4 |url= http://reference.bahai.org/en/t/je/BNE/}}</ref>\n\n[[Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h]] claimed that his mission as the Promised One of the [[B\u00e1b]], was revealed to Him in 1852 while imprisoned in the [[S\u00edy\u00e1h-Ch\u00e1l]] in [[Tehran]], [[Iran]].<ref name=\"eor\" /> After his release from the S\u00edy\u00e1h-Ch\u00e1l, Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h was banished from Persia, and he settled in [[Baghdad]], which became the centre of B\u00e1b\u00ed activity.  Although he did not openly declare this prophetic mandate, he increasingly became the leader of the B\u00e1b\u00ed community.<ref name=\"deepen\">{{Cite journal | first = Bijan | last = Ma'sumian | title = Baha'u'llah's Seclusion in Kurdistan |volume = 1 | issue = 1 | pages =18\u201326 |journal=Deepen Magazine| date = Fall 1993 | url = http://bahai-library.com/masumian_bahaullah_kurdistan}}</ref>\n\nBah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h's rising prominence in the city, and the revival of the Persian B\u00e1b\u00ed community, gained the attention of his enemies in [[Islamic]] clergy and the [[Qajar dynasty|Persian government]].  They were eventually successful in having the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman government]] summon Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h from Baghdad to [[Constantinople]] (present-day [[Istanbul]]).<ref name=\"britannica\">{{cite encyclopedia | year = 1988 | title = The Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Faith | encyclopedia = Britannica Book of the Year | publisher = Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica | location = Chicago | isbn = 0-85229-486-7 | url = https://archive.org/details/1988britannicabo0000daum }}</ref>\n\n===Najibiyyih garden===\n{{See also|Garden of Ridv\u00e1n, Baghdad}}\n[[Image:Ridvan-garden-baghdad.jpg|thumb|Garden of Ridv\u00e1n, Baghdad]]\nBefore Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h left for Constantinople, many visitors came to visit him.  To allow his family to prepare for the trip, and to be able to receive all these visitors, he decided to move to the [[Garden of Ridv\u00e1n, Baghdad|Najibiyyih garden]] across the [[Tigris river]] from Baghdad.  He entered the garden on 22 April 1863 (31 days after [[Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Naw-R\u00faz|Naw R\u00faz]], which usually occurs on 21 March) accompanied by his sons [[\u02bbAbdu'l-Bah\u00e1]], [[M\u00edrz\u00e1 Mihd\u00ed]] and [[M\u00edrz\u00e1 Muhammad \u02bbAl\u00ed]], his secretary Mirza Aqa Jan and some others, and stayed there for eleven days.<ref name=\"rob1_1\" /><ref name=\"walbridge\">{{cite book | title = Sacred Acts, Sacred Space, Sacred Time | first = John | last = Walbridge | year = 2005| url = http://bahai-library.com/walbridge_encyclopedia_ridvan | publisher = George Ronald | location = Oxford, UK | isbn = 0-85398-406-9}}</ref>\n\nAfter his arrival in the garden, Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h announced his mission and station for the first time to a small group of family and friends.  The exact nature and details of Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h's declaration are unknown.  [[Bah\u00edyyih Kh\u00e1num]] is reported to have said that Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h stated his claim to his son [[\u02bbAbdu'l-Bah\u00e1]] and four others.  While some B\u00e1b\u00eds had come to the realization that Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h was claiming to be the Promised One through the many remarks and allusions that he had made during his final few months in Baghdad, it appears that most other B\u00e1b\u00eds were unaware of Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h's claim until a few years later while he was in [[Edirne]].<ref name=\"walbridge\" />\n\nFor the next eleven days Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h received visitors including the governor of Baghdad.  Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h's family was not able to join Him until 30 April, the ninth day, since the river had risen and made travel to the garden difficult though lasting only nine days was a comparatively mild flooding of the river.<ref>{{cite book|author=Charles Issawi Bayard Dodge Professor of Near Eastern Studies Princeton University|title=The Fertile Crescent, 1800\u20131914 : A Documentary Economic History: A Documentary Economic History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F2TGkO7G43oC&pg=PA105|date=14 July 1988|publisher=Oxford University Press, USA|isbn=978-0-19-536421-7|page=105}}</ref> On the twelfth day of their stay in the garden, Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h and his family left the garden and started on their journey to Constantinople.<ref name=\"walbridge\" />\n\n==Festival==\nIn the [[Kit\u00e1b-i-Aqdas]], written during 1873, Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h ordains Ridv\u00e1n as one of two \"Most Great Festivals\", along with the Declaration of the [[B\u00e1b]]. He then specified the first, ninth, and twelfth days to be holy days; these days mark the days of Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h's arrival, the arrival of his family and their departure from the Ridv\u00e1n garden, respectively.<ref name =\"aqdas_notes\">{{cite book |author=Universal House of Justice |year=1992 |title=The Kit\u00e1b-i-Aqdas | chapter = Notes |publisher=Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Publishing Trust |location=Wilmette, Illinois, USA |isbn=0-85398-999-0 |chapter-url=http://reference.bahai.org/en/t/b/KA/ka-155.html.iso8859-1#gr1 | pages = 213\u2013225}}</ref>\n\nThe Festival of Ridv\u00e1n is observed according to the [[Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed calendar]], and begins on the thirty-second day of the Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed year, which falls on 20 or 21 April.  The festival properly starts at two hours before sunset on that day, which symbolises the time that Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h entered the garden. On the first, ninth, and twelfth days, which are [[Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed calendar#Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Holy Days|Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Holy Days]], work is prohibited. Currently, the three holy days are usually observed with a community gathering where prayers are shared, followed with a celebration.<ref name=\"walbridge\" />\n\n==Significance==\nThe time that Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h spent at the Garden of Ridv\u00e1n in April 1863, and the associated festival and celebration, has a very large significance for Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00eds. Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h calls it one of two \"Most Great Festivals\" and describes the first day as \"the Day of supreme felicity\" and he then describes the Garden of Ridvan as \"the Spot from which He shed upon the whole of creation the splendours of his Name, the All-Merciful\".<ref name =\"aqdas_notes\" /><ref name=\"aqdas\">{{cite book |author = Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h |authorlink = Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h |origyear = 1873 |year = 1992 |title = The Kit\u00e1b-i-Aqdas: The Most Holy Book |publisher = Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Publishing Trust |location = Wilmette, Illinois, USA |isbn = 0-85398-999-0 |url = http://reference.bahai.org/en/t/b/KA/ka-6.html.iso8859-1#gr110 | page = 59}}</ref>\n\nThe festival is significant because of Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h's private declaration to a few followers that he was \"Him Whom God shall make manifest\" and a [[Manifestation of God]], and thus it forms the beginning point of the [[Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Faith]], as distinct from the Babi religion.  It is also significant because Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h left his [[Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed pilgrimage#House of Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h, Baghdad|house in Baghdad]], which he designated the \"Most Great House\", to enter the Garden of Ridv\u00e1n. Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h compares this move from the Most Great House to the Garden of Ridv\u00e1n to [[Muhammad]]'s [[Hijra (Islam)|travel from]] [[Mecca]] to [[Medina]].\n\nFurthermore, during Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h's first day in the garden, he made three further announcements: (1) abrogating [[religious war]], which was permitted under certain conditions in [[Islam]] and the B\u00e1b\u00ed faith; (2) that there would not be [[Bah\u00e1{{hamza}}\u00ed prophecies#The next Manifestation of God|another Manifestation of God]] for another 1,000 years; and (3) that all the [[Names of God#Bah\u00e1{{hamza}}\u00ed Faith|names of God]] were fully manifest in all things.<ref name=\"walbridge\" /> These statements appear in a text written some years after 1863, which has been included in the compilation ''[[Days of Remembrance]]'' (section 9). Nader Saiedi states that these three principles are \"affirmed, expounded, and institutionalized\" in Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h's ''[[Kitab-i-Aqdas]]'', which was completed in 1873.<ref>{{cite book | last      = Saiedi | first     = Nader | year      = 2000 | title     = Logos and Civilization \u2013 Spirit, History, and Order in the Writings of Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h | publisher = University Press of Maryland and Association for Baha'i Studies\n | location  = USA | isbn      = 1883053609 | ol = 8685020M | pages     = 243\u2013258 }}</ref>\n\n{{See also|Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed teachings}}\n\n==Related texts==\nThroughout his life, Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h wrote several [[Tablet (religious)|tablets]] and prayers on the occasion of Ridv\u00e1n, among which are the following.\n\n* ''H\u00far-i-\u02bbUj\u00e1b'' (''Tablet of the [[Maid of Heaven|Wondrous Maiden]]'')<ref name=\"Smith-writings\">{{cite encyclopedia |last= Smith |first= Peter|authorlink= Peter Smith (historian) |encyclopedia= A concise encyclopedia of the Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Faith |title= Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h, writings of |year= 2000 |publisher=Oneworld Publications |location= Oxford |isbn= 1-85168-184-1 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=pYfrAQAAQBAJ |pages= 79\u201386}}</ref> \n* ''Lawh-i-\u02bb\u00c1shiq va Ma\u02bbsh\u00faq'' (''Tablet of the Lover and the Beloved'')\n* ''S\u00fariy-i-Qalam'' (''S\u00farih of the Pen'')\n\nThese and several others are published in the volume titled ''[[Days of Remembrance]]''\n\n==Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed elections==\nThe Ridv\u00e1n period is also the time when [[Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed elections]] for the local and national [[Spiritual Assembly|Spiritual Assemblies]] take place every year, as well as the election of the [[Universal House of Justice]], every five years.<ref name=\"SmithRidvan\" />\n\n==Ridv\u00e1n messages==\nAnnually, during Ridv\u00e1n, the Universal House of Justice sends a 'Ridv\u00e1n message' to the worldwide Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed community,<ref name=\"SmithRidvan\" /> which generally gives looks back on the previous year, and provides further guidance for the coming year.<ref group=note>All Ridv\u00e1n messages can be found at [http://www.bahai.org/library/authoritative-texts/the-universal-house-of-justice/messages Bahai.org] and [http://bahaiprayers.net/Ridvan Bahaiprayers.net/Ridvan] (multi-lingual).</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Garden of Ridv\u00e1n, Akka]]\n\n==Notes and citations==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book\n|author = Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h\n|authorlink = Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h\n|origyear = 1873\n|year = 1992\n|title = The Kit\u00e1b-i-Aqdas: The Most Holy Book\n|publisher = Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Publishing Trust\n|location = Wilmette, Illinois, USA\n|isbn = 0-85398-999-0\n|url = http://reference.bahai.org/en/t/b/KA/\n}}\n*{{cite book\n|title = The Master in \u02bbAkka: Including the Recollections of the Greatest Holy Leaf\n|first = Myron H.\n|last = Phelps\n |author2=Bah\u00edyyih Kh\u00e1num |author3=Gail, Marzieh\n|year = 1985\n|publisher = Kalim\u00e1t Press\n|location = Los Angeles\n|isbn = 0-933770-49-9\n}}\n*{{cite book\n|first = Adib\n|last = Taherzadeh\n|authorlink = Adib Taherzadeh\n|year = 1976\n|title = The Revelation of Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h, Volume 1\n|publisher = George Ronald\n|location = Oxford, UK\n|isbn = 0-85398-270-8\n|url = http://www.peyman.info/cl/Baha%27i/Others/ROB/V1/Cover.html\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed World Centre]] (2017). ''[[Days of Remembrance|Days of Remembrance \u2013 Selections from the Writings of Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h for Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Holy Days]].''\n* [http://www.bahai-library.com/tags/Ridvan Related documents on Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Library Online]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://bahai9.com/wiki/Lawh-i-Ridv%C3%A1n_I A compendium on Ridv\u00e1n]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ridvan}}\n[[Category:Bah\u00e1'\u00ed holy days]]\n[[Category:April observances]]\n[[Category:May observances]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Turkish given name|Ridvan}}\n{{short description|Twelve-day festival in the Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Faith, commemorating Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h's declaration that he was a Manifestation of God}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed sidebar}}\n'''Ri\u1e0dv\u00e1n''' ({{lang-ar|\u0631\u0636\u0648\u0627\u0646}} {{transl|ar|Ri\u1e0dw\u00e1n}}; [[Persian language|Persian]] [[Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed orthography|transliteration]]: Rezv\u00e1n, {{IPA-fa|\u027eezv\u0252\u02d0n}}) is a twelve-day festival in the [[Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Faith]], commemorating [[Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h]]'s declaration that he was a [[Manifestation of God]].<ref name=\"SmithRidvan\">{{cite encyclopedia |last= Smith |first= Peter |authorlink= Peter Smith (historian) |encyclopedia= A concise encyclopedia of the Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Faith |title= Ridvan |year= 2000 |publisher= Oneworld Publications |location= Oxford |pages= [https://archive.org/details/conciseencyclope0000smit/page/296 296\u2013297] |isbn= 1-85168-184-1 |url= https://archive.org/details/conciseencyclope0000smit/page/296 }}</ref> In the [[Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Calendar]], it begins at sunset on the 13th of Jal\u00e1l, which translates to the 20th or 21st of April, depending on the date of the [[March equinox]] (exactly one month on the Gregorian calendar after the equinox).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bahai-library.com/holy_days_calendar_students |title=Baha'i Dates 172\u2013221 B.E. |website=Baha'i Library |language=en-US |access-date=2018-04-20}}</ref> On the first, ninth and twelfth days of Ridv\u00e1n, work and school should be suspended.<ref name=\"esslemont_1\">{{cite book |author= Esslemont, J.E. |year= 1980 |title= Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h and the New Era |edition= 5th |publisher=Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Publishing Trust |location=Wilmette, Illinois, USA |isbn= 0-87743-160-4 |url= http://reference.bahai.org/en/t/je/BNE/bne-147.html | pages = 182\u2013183}}</ref>\n\n\"Ridv\u00e1n\" means [[paradise]], and is named for the [[Garden of Ridv\u00e1n, Baghdad|Garden of Ridv\u00e1n]] outside [[Baghdad]], where Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h stayed for twelve days after the [[Ottoman Empire]] exiled him from the city and before commencing his journey to [[Constantinople]].<ref name=\"rob1_1\">{{cite book |first=Adib |last= Taherzadeh |year= 1976 |title= The Revelation of Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h, Volume 1 |publisher= George Ronald |location=Oxford, UK |isbn= 0-85398-270-8 |page= 259 |url= http://www.peyman.info/cl/Baha%27i/Others/ROB/V1/p257-282Ch16.html#p259}}</ref>\n\nIt is the holiest Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed festival, and is also referred to as the \"Most Great Festival\" and the \"King of Festivals\".\n\n==History==\n===Context===\nIn 1844 Siyyid [[\u02bbAl\u00ed-Muhammad of Shiraz]] proclaimed that he was the \"[[B\u00e1b]]\" ({{lang-ar|\"Gate\"}}), after a [[Shi\u02bba Islam|Shi\u02bba]] religious concept. His followers were therefore known as [[B\u00e1bism|B\u00e1b\u00eds]].  The B\u00e1b's writings introduced the concept of \"[[He whom God shall make manifest]]\", a Messianic figure whose coming, according to Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00eds, was announced in the scriptures of all of the world's great religions.<ref name=\"eor\">{{cite encyclopedia | last = Hutter | first = Manfred | editor = Ed. Lindsay Jones | encyclopedia = Encyclopedia of Religion | title = B\u0101b\u012bs | edition = 2nd | year = 2005 | publisher = [[Macmillan Reference USA]] | volume = 2 | location = Detroit | pages = 727\u2013729 | isbn = 0-02-865733-0 | url = https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofre0000unse_v8f2 }}</ref><ref name=\"esslemont\">{{cite book |author= Esslemont, J.E. |year= 1980 |title= Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h and the New Era |edition= 5th |publisher=Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Publishing Trust |location=Wilmette, Illinois, USA |isbn= 0-87743-160-4 |url= http://reference.bahai.org/en/t/je/BNE/}}</ref>\n\n[[Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h]] claimed that his mission as the Promised One of the [[B\u00e1b]], was revealed to Him in 1852 while imprisoned in the [[S\u00edy\u00e1h-Ch\u00e1l]] in [[Tehran]], [[Iran]].<ref name=\"eor\" /> After his release from the S\u00edy\u00e1h-Ch\u00e1l, Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h was banished from Persia, and he settled in [[Baghdad]], which became the centre of B\u00e1b\u00ed activity.  Although he did not openly declare this prophetic mandate, he increasingly became the leader of the B\u00e1b\u00ed community.<ref name=\"deepen\">{{Cite journal | first = Bijan | last = Ma'sumian | title = Baha'u'llah's Seclusion in Kurdistan |volume = 1 | issue = 1 | pages =18\u201326 |journal=Deepen Magazine| date = Fall 1993 | url = http://bahai-library.com/masumian_bahaullah_kurdistan}}</ref>\n\nBah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h's rising prominence in the city, and the revival of the Persian B\u00e1b\u00ed community, gained the attention of his enemies in [[Islamic]] clergy and the [[Qajar dynasty|Persian government]].  They were eventually successful in having the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman government]] summon Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h from Baghdad to [[Constantinople]] (present-day [[Istanbul]]).<ref name=\"britannica\">{{cite encyclopedia | year = 1988 | title = The Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Faith | encyclopedia = Britannica Book of the Year | publisher = Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica | location = Chicago | isbn = 0-85229-486-7 | url = https://archive.org/details/1988britannicabo0000daum }}</ref>\n\n===Najibiyyih garden===\n{{See also|Garden of Ridv\u00e1n, Baghdad}}\n[[Image:Ridvan-garden-baghdad.jpg|thumb|Garden of Ridv\u00e1n, Baghdad]]\nBefore Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h left for Constantinople, many visitors came to visit him.  To allow his family to prepare for the trip, and to be able to receive all these visitors, he decided to move to the [[Garden of Ridv\u00e1n, Baghdad|Najibiyyih garden]] across the [[Tigris river]] from Baghdad.  He entered the garden on 22 April 1863 (31 days after [[Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Naw-R\u00faz|Naw R\u00faz]], which usually occurs on 21 March) accompanied by his sons [[\u02bbAbdu'l-Bah\u00e1]], [[M\u00edrz\u00e1 Mihd\u00ed]] and [[M\u00edrz\u00e1 Muhammad \u02bbAl\u00ed]], his secretary Mirza Aqa Jan and some others, and stayed there for eleven days.<ref name=\"rob1_1\" /><ref name=\"walbridge\">{{cite book | title = Sacred Acts, Sacred Space, Sacred Time | first = John | last = Walbridge | year = 2005| url = http://bahai-library.com/walbridge_encyclopedia_ridvan | publisher = George Ronald | location = Oxford, UK | isbn = 0-85398-406-9}}</ref>\n\nAfter his arrival in the garden, Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h announced his mission and station for the first time to a small group of family and friends.  The exact nature and details of Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h's declaration are unknown.  [[Bah\u00edyyih Kh\u00e1num]] is reported to have said that Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h stated his claim to his son [[\u02bbAbdu'l-Bah\u00e1]] and four others.  While some B\u00e1b\u00eds had come to the realization that Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h was claiming to be the Promised One through the many remarks and allusions that he had made during his final few months in Baghdad, it appears that most other B\u00e1b\u00eds were unaware of Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h's claim until a few years later while he was in [[Edirne]].<ref name=\"walbridge\" />\n\nFor the next eleven days Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h received visitors including the governor of Baghdad.  Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h's family was not able to join Him until 30 April, the ninth day, since the river had risen and made travel to the garden difficult though lasting only nine days was a comparatively mild flooding of the river.<ref>{{cite book|author=Charles Issawi Bayard Dodge Professor of Near Eastern Studies Princeton University|title=The Fertile Crescent, 1800\u20131914 : A Documentary Economic History: A Documentary Economic History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F2TGkO7G43oC&pg=PA105|date=14 July 1988|publisher=Oxford University Press, USA|isbn=978-0-19-536421-7|page=105}}</ref> On the twelfth day of their stay in the garden, Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h and his family left the garden and started on their journey to Constantinople.<ref name=\"walbridge\" />\n\n==Festival==\nIn the [[Kit\u00e1b-i-Aqdas]], written during 1873, Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h ordains Ridv\u00e1n as one of two \"Most Great Festivals\", along with the Declaration of the [[B\u00e1b]]. He then specified the first, ninth, and twelfth days to be holy days; these days mark the days of Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h's arrival, the arrival of his family and their departure from the Ridv\u00e1n garden, respectively.<ref name =\"aqdas_notes\">{{cite book |author=Universal House of Justice |year=1992 |title=The Kit\u00e1b-i-Aqdas | chapter = Notes |publisher=Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Publishing Trust |location=Wilmette, Illinois, USA |isbn=0-85398-999-0 |chapter-url=http://reference.bahai.org/en/t/b/KA/ka-155.html.iso8859-1#gr1 | pages = 213\u2013225}}</ref>\n\nThe Festival of Ridv\u00e1n is observed according to the [[Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed calendar]], and begins on the thirty-second day of the Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed year, which falls on 20 or 21 April.  The festival properly starts at two hours before sunset on that day, which symbolises the time that Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h entered the garden. On the first, ninth, and twelfth days, which are [[Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed calendar#Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Holy Days|Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Holy Days]], work is prohibited. Currently, the three holy days are usually observed with a community gathering where prayers are shared, followed with a celebration.<ref name=\"walbridge\" />\n\n==Significance==\nThe time that Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h spent at the Garden of Ridv\u00e1n in April 1863, and the associated festival and celebration, has a very large significance for Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00eds. Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h calls it one of two \"Most Great Festivals\" and describes the first day as \"the Day of supreme felicity\" and he then describes the Garden of Ridvan as \"the Spot from which He shed upon the whole of creation the splendours of his Name, the All-Merciful\".<ref name =\"aqdas_notes\" /><ref name=\"aqdas\">{{cite book |author = Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h |authorlink = Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h |origyear = 1873 |year = 1992 |title = The Kit\u00e1b-i-Aqdas: The Most Holy Book |publisher = Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Publishing Trust |location = Wilmette, Illinois, USA |isbn = 0-85398-999-0 |url = http://reference.bahai.org/en/t/b/KA/ka-6.html.iso8859-1#gr110 | page = 59}}</ref>\n\nThe festival is significant because of Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h's private declaration to a few followers that he was \"Him Whom God shall make manifest\" and a [[Manifestation of God]], and thus it forms the beginning point of the [[Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Faith]], as distinct from the Babi religion.  It is also significant because Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h left his [[Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed pilgrimage#House of Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h, Baghdad|house in Baghdad]], which he designated the \"Most Great House\", to enter the Garden of Ridv\u00e1n. Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h compares this move from the Most Great House to the Garden of Ridv\u00e1n to [[Muhammad]]'s [[Hijra (Islam)|travel from]] [[Mecca]] to [[Medina]].\n\nFurthermore, during Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h's first day in the garden, he made three further announcements: (1) abrogating [[religious war]], which was permitted under certain conditions in [[Islam]] and the B\u00e1b\u00ed faith; (2) that there would not be [[Bah\u00e1{{hamza}}\u00ed prophecies#The next Manifestation of God|another Manifestation of God]] for another 1,000 years; and (3) that all the [[Names of God#Bah\u00e1{{hamza}}\u00ed Faith|names of God]] were fully manifest in all things.<ref name=\"walbridge\" /> These statements appear in a text written some years after 1863, which has been included in the compilation ''[[Days of Remembrance]]'' (section 9). Nader Saiedi states that these three principles are \"affirmed, expounded, and institutionalized\" in Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h's ''[[Kitab-i-Aqdas]]'', which was completed in 1873.<ref>{{cite book | last      = Saiedi | first     = Nader | year      = 2000 | title     = Logos and Civilization \u2013 Spirit, History, and Order in the Writings of Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h | publisher = University Press of Maryland and Association for Baha'i Studies\n | location  = USA | isbn      = 1883053609 | ol = 8685020M | pages     = 243\u2013258 }}</ref>\n\n{{See also|Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed teachings}}\n\n==Related texts==\nThroughout his life, Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h wrote several [[Tablet (religious)|tablets]] and prayers on the occasion of Ridv\u00e1n, among which are the following.\n\n* ''H\u00far-i-\u02bbUj\u00e1b'' (''Tablet of the [[Maid of Heaven|Wondrous Maiden]]'')<ref name=\"Smith-writings\">{{cite encyclopedia |last= Smith |first= Peter|authorlink= Peter Smith (historian) |encyclopedia= A concise encyclopedia of the Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Faith |title= Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h, writings of |year= 2000 |publisher=Oneworld Publications |location= Oxford |isbn= 1-85168-184-1 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=pYfrAQAAQBAJ |pages= 79\u201386}}</ref> \n* ''Lawh-i-\u02bb\u00c1shiq va Ma\u02bbsh\u00faq'' (''Tablet of the Lover and the Beloved'')\n* ''S\u00fariy-i-Qalam'' (''S\u00farih of the Pen'')\n\nThese and several others are published in the volume titled ''[[Days of Remembrance]]''\n\n==Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed elections==\nThe Ridv\u00e1n period is also the time when [[Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed elections]] for the local and national [[Spiritual Assembly|Spiritual Assemblies]] take place every year, as well as the election of the [[Universal House of Justice]], every five years.<ref name=\"SmithRidvan\" />\n\n==Ridv\u00e1n messages==\nAnnually, during Ridv\u00e1n, the Universal House of Justice sends a 'Ridv\u00e1n message' to the worldwide Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed community,<ref name=\"SmithRidvan\" /> which generally gives looks back on the previous year, and provides further guidance for the coming year.<ref group=note>All Ridv\u00e1n messages can be found at [http://www.bahai.org/library/authoritative-texts/the-universal-house-of-justice/messages Bahai.org] and [http://bahaiprayers.net/Ridvan Bahaiprayers.net/Ridvan] (multi-lingual).</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Garden of Ridv\u00e1n, Akka]]\n\n==Notes and citations==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book\n|author = Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h\n|authorlink = Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h\n|origyear = 1873\n|year = 1992\n|title = The Kit\u00e1b-i-Aqdas: The Most Holy Book\n|publisher = Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Publishing Trust\n|location = Wilmette, Illinois, USA\n|isbn = 0-85398-999-0\n|url = http://reference.bahai.org/en/t/b/KA/\n}}\n*{{cite book\n|title = The Master in \u02bbAkka: Including the Recollections of the Greatest Holy Leaf\n|first = Myron H.\n|last = Phelps\n |author2=Bah\u00edyyih Kh\u00e1num |author3=Gail, Marzieh\n|year = 1985\n|publisher = Kalim\u00e1t Press\n|location = Los Angeles\n|isbn = 0-933770-49-9\n}}\n*{{cite book\n|first = Adib\n|last = Taherzadeh\n|authorlink = Adib Taherzadeh\n|year = 1976\n|title = The Revelation of Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h, Volume 1\n|publisher = George Ronald\n|location = Oxford, UK\n|isbn = 0-85398-270-8\n|url = http://www.peyman.info/cl/Baha%27i/Others/ROB/V1/Cover.html\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed World Centre]] (2017). ''[[Days of Remembrance|Days of Remembrance \u2013 Selections from the Writings of Bah\u00e1\u02bcu'll\u00e1h for Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Holy Days]].''\n* [http://www.bahai-library.com/tags/Ridvan Related documents on Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Library Online]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://bahai9.com/wiki/Lawh-i-Ridv%C3%A1n_I A compendium on Ridv\u00e1n]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ridvan}}\n[[Category:Bah\u00e1'\u00ed holy days]]\n[[Category:April observances]]\n[[Category:May observances]]\n", "name_user": "J S Ayer", "label": "safe", "comment": "turning a red link blue", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ridv%C3%A1n"}
